  "texts": [
    "It should be noted that this solution could introduce its own set of problems regarding how researchers should prioritize these efforts relative to other activities.",
    "Additionally, metrics of time and effort might be more complex and more difficult to understand than ones based on counting output.",
    "Incentivizing quality over quantity.",
    "Even without developing alternative metrics, there are some easy and relatively minor changes to academic evaluation that could alter narrow incentive structures.",
    "For example, one possibility that avoids some of the pernicious effects of counting citations is for researchers to indicate and describe their top n publications (where n is relatively small, such as 5 or 10, and determined by the field) in the past m years (where m is again determined by the field), thus incentivizing quality over quantity (also see the article \"Alternative Models of Research Funding\" in this special feature for a discussion of these issues)."
  ],
